    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for this house i'm buying in toronto. what actually is escrow and why can't i just pay the seller directly?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, a vital component of the home-buying process, is a trust account that holds funds until certain conditions are met. It's a safety net, if you will, to ensure that the transaction unfolds smoothly. You see, escrow is like a temporary holding cell for your down payment, allowing you to release funds only when the seller has fulfilled their obligations, such as completing repairs or removing any liens on the property. This way, you're protected from any potential disputes or issues that might arise during the transaction.\n\nNow, you might wonder why you can't just pay the seller directly. Well, think of it like this: if you were to hand over the cash to the seller, it would be like giving them a big ol' gift, without any guarantees that they'll follow through on their commitments. Escrow provides a level of assurance, ensuring that the funds are released only when all parties have fulfilled their obligations. It's a bit like having a team of diligent, no-nonsense accountants watching over the transaction, making sure everything adds up correctly.",
      "source": "target",
