    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so who actually holds the money? like is it the realtor or some specific bank, and how do they make sure they don't just mess it up or lose it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The escrow account is typically held by a third-party escrow company, which is usually a specialized bank or a financial institution that's experienced in handling these types of transactions. These companies have a reputation for being reliable and trustworthy, and they're often regulated by government agencies to ensure their integrity.\n\nThe escrow company acts as a neutral third party, holding the funds until the conditions of the sale are met. They're like a referee, making sure everyone plays by the rules. When the sale is complete, the escrow company releases the funds to the buyer, and the seller receives their payment.\n\nTo prevent any mischief, the escrow company has a system in place to monitor the funds and ensure they're being used correctly. They might have multiple layers of security, like separate accounts and audits, to prevent any unauthorized access or tampering. It's a bit like having a team of skilled, detail-oriented accountants working on the transaction, making sure everything is accurate and on track.\n\nAnd, just like a well-run household, the escrow company has its own set of rules and protocols to ensure the smooth operation of the escrow account. They're like a team of diligent, no-nonsense accountants, making sure everything adds up correctly",
